# Day 10 – Linux Process Management & Network Switches

## 🎯 Objective

Today's objective was to understand Linux processes, learn how to monitor and manage running processes using command-line tools, and study how network switches forward Ethernet frames using MAC addresses.

---

# 🐧 Linux Theory

## What is a Process?

A process is a program that is currently running on a Linux system.

Examples of processes include:

- Terminal
- Firefox
- File Manager
- VS Code
- htop

Every running process has a unique Process ID (PID).

---

## Process ID (PID)

A PID is a unique number assigned to every running process.

Linux uses the PID to identify and manage processes.

Example:

PID 1250 → Firefox

PID 2135 → Terminal

---

## Foreground vs Background Processes

### Foreground Process

Runs directly in the terminal and blocks it until the process finishes.

Example:

```bash
ping google.com
```

---

### Background Process

Runs without blocking the terminal.

Example:

```bash
sleep 300 &
```

The `&` symbol starts the command in the background.

---

## Process Management Commands

| Command | Purpose |
|----------|---------|
| ps | View current processes |
| ps aux | View all running processes |
| top | Live process monitoring |
| htop | Interactive process monitor |
| jobs | View background jobs |
| kill PID | Stop a process |
| kill -9 PID | Forcefully terminate a process |

---

## Difference Between `top` and `htop`

| top | htop |
|-----|------|
| Basic interface | Interactive interface |
| Keyboard navigation limited | Easy navigation |
| Installed by default | Usually installed manually |

---

# 🌐 Networking Theory

## What is a Network Switch?

A switch is a networking device that connects multiple devices within the same Local Area Network (LAN).

Unlike a hub, a switch sends data only to the intended destination device.

---

## How a Switch Works

A switch learns the MAC address connected to each port.

When a frame arrives, the switch checks its MAC Address Table (CAM Table) and forwards the frame only to the correct port.

---

## MAC Address Table (CAM Table)

Example:

| MAC Address | Port |
|--------------|------|
| AA:BB:CC:11:22:33 | Port 1 |
| DD:EE:FF:44:55:66 | Port 2 |

This improves efficiency and reduces unnecessary network traffic.

---

## Hub vs Switch

| Hub | Switch |
|------|---------|
| Broadcasts data to all devices | Sends data only to the destination |
| Slower | Faster |
| More collisions | Fewer collisions |
| No MAC table | Uses CAM table |

---

## Broadcast Domain

A broadcast domain is a group of devices that receive broadcast traffic.

By default, all devices connected to the same switch are in the same broadcast domain unless VLANs are configured.

